-- Italian Stocks Fall; Elica, Eni, Fiat, Finmeccanica, UniCredit Are Active
-- Tommaso Ebhardt
-- 2010-07-19T15:54:07Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-19/fiat-finmeccanica-intesa-saras-may-move-italy-equity-market-preview.html

          
          
             Italy’s benchmark FTSE MIB Index
fell 43.48, or 0.2 percent, to 20,117.54 in Milan.  
 The following stocks were among the most active in the
Italian market today.  
 Elica SpA  (ELC IM) rose 2.1 percent to 1.66 euros, the
highest since June 23, after it bought a 55 percent stake in the
Chinese company Zhejiang Putian Electric Co. Ltd.  
 Eni SpA  (ENI IM), Italy’s biggest oil company, gained 4
cents, or 0.4 percent, to 15.32 euros. Italy’s biggest energy
company said today that it started offshore gas production from
the Tuna field in Egypt.  
 Fiat SpA  (F IM) fell 1 cent, or 0.1 percent, to 9.25 euros.
The Italian carmaker that runs Chrysler Group LLC agreed with
banks to refinance 4 billion euros ($5.2 billion) of debt before
the spinoff of its industrial unit, Il Sole 24 Ore reported.  
 Finmeccanica SpA  (FNC IM) dropped 1.5 cents, or 0.2
percent, to 8.56 euros. Italy’s biggest defense company, expects
more than 22 billion euros of orders in 2011, Italian newswire
Radiocor said, citing a press conference at the Farnborough Air
Show Today.  
 Gruppo Editoriale L’Espresso SpA  (ES IM), an Italian
publisher, gained 4.4 cents, or 3.1 percent, to 1.47 euros after
it was raised to “buy” from “hold” at Deutsche Bank.  
 UniCredit SpA (UCG IM), Italy’s biggest bank, fell for a
fourth day, slipping 0.7 percent to 1.98 euros. UniCredit Bank
Austria AG said Austrian lenders may require 5 billion euros to
20 billion euros because of new capital requirements from Basel
III, according to a study.  
